@candicegjing for your specific question, I believe that's what was happening. 

As for performance vs accuracy, this is a spot where we can't afford to have any inaccuracy because if we assign too many jobs to a worker, they simply fail. Because of that, any caching/perf improvement has to guarantee not breaking the correctness of resource calculations for workers. 

In this case, I don't think falling back to the db call would affect performance anyways because you cache all the running bundles AND the staged bundles, so it's a very small chance we have a non-cached running bundle. And IF that happens, we  have no choice but to fetch the information for it from the database, as otherwise we'll potentially fail existing runs, which is the worst outcome from a user experience perspective.

