The other way would be for the application to specify the size exponent directly, and instead provide a means (macro, inline function) to convert between that and and nearest size… something like:

```
#define OT_COAP_MIN_SZX (0)
#define OT_COAP_MAX_SZX (7)

uint16_t otCoapBlockSizeFromExponent(uint8_t aSzx)
{
    return 1 << (aSzx + 4);
}

uint8_t otCoapNearestSizeExponent(uint16_t aBlockSize)
{
    uint8_t szx;
    for (szx = OT_COAP_MIN_SZX; szx < OT_COAP_MAX_SZX; szx++)
    {
        if (otCoapBlockSizeFromExponent(szx) >= aBlockSize)
        {
            break;
        }
    }

    return szx;
}
```

That will probably need some tweaking, and there may be optimisations that can be made (I took the naïve iterative approach to illustrate), but that will handle arbitrary sizes like 192 bytes, by rounding up to the nearest block size (256 in that case).

Then application writers can bounce either way.  The C compiler may even be smart enough if given a constant to `otCoapNearestSizeExponent`, that the result never changes and so replace the function call with a constant.  The return value of `otCoapNearestSizeExponent` could possibly be cast to that `enum` as well.

