Nice catch—it does borrowck without, so I’ll remove it. I probably
reflexively added it because we use `keep_steps` inside the closure, but
it’s not needed because `keep_steps: usize` is `Copy`, and also because
we only use `&mut keep_steps`, anyway (implicitly, via `.next()`).

I think the right mental model for closures is just to desugar them—

```rust
struct MyClosure {
    things_moved_into_it: u32,
    things_it_closes_over: &str,
}

impl MyClosure {
    fn call(%%%self, args: TArgs) -> TReturn {
        unimplemented!()
    }
}
```

—where `%%%self` is either `self` for a `FnOnce`, `&self` for a `Fn`, or
`&mut self` for a `FnMut`. Then the normal borrowck rules will guide you
to whether something’s legal. So even with `move ||`, it’d be illegal to
write something like

```rust
fn main() {
    let four = String::from("four");
    let mut v = vec!["jumped", "over", "the", "lazy", "dog"];
    v.retain(move |s| {  // this is a `FnMut`, per `Vec::retain`
        // Try to move `four` via closure: can't, because you may have
        // moved it on a previous iteration.
        let to_check = four;
        s.len() == to_check.len()
    });
    dbg!(v);
}
```

because this is analogous to “cannot move out of borrowed content”:

```rust
struct MyClosure {
    four: String,
}

impl MyClosure {
    fn call(&mut self, s: &str) -> bool {
        let to_check = self.four; // cannot move out of borrowed content
        s.len() == to_check.len()
    }
}
```

(i.e., moving _into_ the closure is fine; it’s moving _out_ of it that’s
the problem here).

`move` can still be useful outside of threads; e.g.:

```rust
fn printer(s: String) -> impl Fn() -> () {
    move || { // this `move` is required for the program to compile
        println!("you said: {:?}", s);
    }
}

fn main() {
    let mut printers: Vec<Box<dyn Fn() -> ()>> = Vec::new();
    printers.push(Box::new(printer("hello".to_string())));
    printers.push(Box::new(printer("world".to_string())));
    for p in printers {
        p();
        p();
    }
}
```

Here maybe it’s easier to see that `s: String` is moved into the closure
when it’s constructed.

