Okay this line likely need to be explained....

Normally we are using the ``_call`` or ``_use`` pattern  not the ``_claim``.   In a ``_use`` we are given an existing reference that we need to ensure we don't lose the reference to (like stupid things like manipulating a map and losing the reference to ourselves.   ``_call`` is also obvious because we got a reference an immediately put into a container.  

``_claim`` is an edge case.  We constructed a new reference, but for whatever reason we didn't put it in a reference counter (special error handling etc), but we want it to enter the reference counting system at some later point.

```
   JPPyObject doSomething()
   {

     // We created a reference but we can't throw because it requires a special handling...
    PyObject* obj = PyDo_Something(...);
     //  Next we do whatever checks we need and the handling routines...
    if (obj==NULL)
    {  // handle error
    }
     ...
    // Okay we know that it isn't 0 and but it still isn't in a reference counting frame so it
    // still has a reference count of 1.
   return JPPyObject(JPPyRef::_claim, obj);
   // So something weird happens here.  We claim the object so now it has a reference count 
   // of one and will die at the end of scope, but before that happens the return value will 
  // be constructed which will copy the reference and increment it to 2.  then decrement it 
  // back to 1.
}
```

So the intent of the line is to hold grab the reference and then transfer control to the return.   That said I do not see any reason for using the claim pattern in this case.  There is no special handling of types nor an exceptional return path.  And in some very rare case assignJavaSlot may fail resulting in a leaked object, though given the type system I am nor sure it can be triggered here.  I will convert it to a ``_call`` pattern to be safe.

